cambium.name: cambium

revisions.description: PTP800-05-00: Added objects and traps to support IRFU, and 1+1 hot standby with receive diversity. Added queue mapping objects for L3 QOS. Added securityLevel to the licence group. Added syslogClientTrap. Updated objects and traps for multiple secure SNTP servers. Renamed 'oDU' objects to 'rFU'. Renamed antennaProtection to numberOfAntennas. Renamed 'vLANPriority' objects to 'ethernetPriority'. Renamed 'l2CPQueueMapping' objects to 'l2CPPriority'. Renamed 'fipsOperationalMode' objects to 'secureMode'. Renamed 'motorolaPTP' productVariant enumerations to 'pTP'. Renamed sNTPSynchronizationFailed bit to sNTPSync in enabledDiagnosticAlarms. Renamed activeElapsedTime to activeCounterMeasurementPeriod. Corrected spelling of 'advertisement' attributes.

PTP800-04-00: Renamed oDUIfSynthLockAlarm to oduCommonSynthLockAlarm. Increased range for radioLicenseRegion, radioLicenseBandwidth, transmitCapacityLimitDetail and rFUStatus. Added objects for http, https, and telnet. Added objects and traps for syslog. Replaced single instance of trap receiver with a table.

PTP800-03-00: Added objects and traps to support 1+1 Hot Standby. Updated range and description text for a number of objects. Made enableTransmission read-write. Added enableDiagnosticAlarms. Made byteErrorRatio and codeWordErrorRatio 64 bit counters.
PTP800-02-04: Updated & re-formatted description text. Corrected DisplayString sizes. Changed longitude and latitude types. Updated transmitCapacityLimit & dataPortCopperForcedConfiguration ranges.
PTP800-02-02: Added new phyStatusGroup objects. Updated oDUFreqSpacing & linkLoss ranges.
PTP800-02-01: data & management port status traps, writeable auto-negotiation.
PTP800-02-00: BIT STRING types now OCTET STRING. Added linkName, siteName, & support for l2CPQueueMapping & ACM ranges.

ptpCompliance.description: The compliance statement for the Cambium PTP MIB

ethernetPriorityTable.name: ethernetPriorityTable
ethernetPriorityTable.description: A priority queue mapping table. This is a list of packet queues indexed by Ethernet priority.

l2CPPriorityTable.name: l2CPPriorityTable
l2CPPriorityTable.description: A priority queue mapping table. This is a list of packet queues associated with the different layer 2 control protocol frameworks.

iPDSCPPriorityTable.name: iPDSCPPriorityTable
iPDSCPPriorityTable.description: A priority queue mapping table. This is a list of packet queues indexed by L3 IP DSCP priority.

mPLSTCPriorityTable.name: mPLSTCPriorityTable
mPLSTCPriorityTable.description: A priority queue mapping table. This is a list of priority queues indexed by MPLS TC priority.

localPacketFiltering.name: localPacketFiltering
localPacketFiltering.description: Controls filtering for Ethernet frames that have source or destination address equal to the MAC address of the CMU. When Local Packet Filtering is disabled, frames generated within the management agent are sent to both Ethernet and wireless interfaces. When Local Packet Filtering is enabled, frames generated within the management agent are transmitted at the port learned for the destination address, and frames addressed to the management agent are not bridged

iPAddress.name: iPAddress
iPAddress.description: Internet protocol (IP) address. This address is used by the family of Internet protocols to uniquely identify the unit on a network.

subnetMask.name: subnetMask
subnetMask.description: A subnet allows the flow of network traffic between hosts to be segregated based on a network configuration. By organizing hosts into logical groups, subnetting can improve network security and performance

gatewayIPAddress.name: gatewayIPAddress
gatewayIPAddress.description: The IP address of a computer on the current network that is currently acting as a network gateway. A gateway acts as an entrance / exit to packets from / to other networks.

maximumTransmitPower.name: maximumTransmitPower
maximumTransmitPower.description: Maximum transmit power the wireless unit is permitted to use when establishing and maintaining the wireless link, expressed in tenths of a dBm. Note that when an IRFU is connected rather than an ODU, the transmit power refers to the power at the transceiver output and not the IRFU antenna port. See the User Guide for more details

antennaGain.name: antennaGain
antennaGain.description: Antenna Gain. Expressed in 10ths of dBi.

rFFeederLoss.name: rFFeederLoss
rFFeederLoss.description: Insertion loss of the microwave connection between the RFU and the antenna. The feeder loss should be 0 dB for the standard 1 + 0 direct mount configuration. Expressed in 10ths of dB.

remoteIPAddress.name: remoteIPAddress
remoteIPAddress.description: IP Address of the peer wireless unit

remoteMACAddress.name: remoteMACAddress
remoteMACAddress.description: MAC Address of the peer wireless unit

enableTransmission.name: enableTransmission
enableTransmission.description: Permits the transmitter to radiate. Once the unit is installed and configured, use this to enable the transmitter

aTPCEnable.name: aTPCEnable
aTPCEnable.description: Enables Automatic Transmitter Power Control (ATPC). NOTE: Use of ATPC is mandatory in some regions. When ATPC is enabled, the transmit power is dynamically adjusted to optimize link performance. The transmit power will always be adjusted within the constraints set by Maximum Transmit Power. When ATPC is disabled, the transmit power will be fixed at the level set by Maximum Transmit Power. When adaptive modulation is enabled, this setting can limit the capacity of the system by capping the modulation to a mode which is consistent with the configured Maximum Transmit Power.

iFCableLength.name: iFCableLength
iFCableLength.description: IF Cable Length in cm - please refer to the user manual for more information on the recommended cable type.

linkName.name: linkName
linkName.description: Name of the PTP link allocated by the System Administrator. Used to establish a connection with the correct PTP wireless unit at the other end of the link. NOTE: The link name MUST be the same at both ends of the PTP link.

siteName.name: siteName
siteName.description: This field is allocated by the system administrator and contains a description of the site name together with any additional notes

diverseAntennaGain.name: diverseAntennaGain
diverseAntennaGain.description: Diverse Antenna Receive Gain. Expressed in 10ths of dBi.

diverseRfFeederLoss.name: diverseRfFeederLoss
diverseRfFeederLoss.description: Insertion loss of the microwave connection between the RFU and the diverse antenna. Expressed in 10ths of dB.

dataPortCopperAutoNegotiation.name: dataPortCopperAutoNegotiation
dataPortCopperAutoNegotiation.description: This controls whether the configuration of the copper data Ethernet interface is automatically negotiated or forced. WARNING: ONLY USE FORCED AS A LAST RESORT. To operate an Ethernet link at a fixed speed, leave auto negotiation enabled and limit the Auto Neg Advertisement to the desired speed. Only force Ethernet configuration as a last resort if constrained auto negotiation fails. NB: Auto-MDI/MDIX is disabled when Forced is set, and the unit defaults to MDIX, so the correct straight through or crossover cable will be required to establish a connection. NB: both ends of an Ethernet link must be configured identically, as Forced and auto negotiation are NOT compatible. A mixed configuration will cause a duplex mismatch

dataPortCopperAutoNegAdvertisement.name: dataPortCopperAutoNegAdvertisement
dataPortCopperAutoNegAdvertisement.description: This sets the different configurations of the copper data Ethernet interface that will be advertised during auto negotiation. WARNING: Duplex mismatch may result if both ends of the Ethernet link do not have the same settings. Do not use auto negotiation together with a fixed setting at the Ethernet link partner (other end of the link). WARNING: Make sure that you select option(s) that you know your connected equipment can cater for!

dataPortStatus.name: dataPortStatus
dataPortStatus.description: Current status of the data Ethernet link. NB: a change of state may generate an SNMP trap and/or SMTP email alert

dataPortSpeedAndDuplex.name: dataPortSpeedAndDuplex
dataPortSpeedAndDuplex.description: The current speed and duplex of the data Ethernet link

dataPortWirelessDownAlert.name: dataPortWirelessDownAlert
dataPortWirelessDownAlert.description: When enabled, this causes the data Ethernet link to be dropped briefly when the wireless link drops. This is so that spanning tree algorithms can quickly detect that there is a problem

useVLANForManagementInterfaces.name: useVLANForManagementInterfaces
useVLANForManagementInterfaces.description: This controls whether the management interfaces (WWW/SNMP/SMTP/SNTP) use VLAN tags or not

vLANManagementPriority.name: vLANManagementPriority
vLANManagementPriority.description: This VLAN Priority (0-7) will be included in packets generated by the management interfaces

vLANManagementVIDValidation.name: vLANManagementVIDValidation
vLANManagementVIDValidation.description: If enabled, the management interfaces will only respond to Ethernet packets tagged with the configured VLAN Management VID, otherwise packets with any VID will be accepted

vLANManagementVID.name: vLANManagementVID
vLANManagementVID.description: This VLAN VID (0-4094) will be included in packets generated by the management interfaces

ethernetPriorityTableNumber.name: ethernetPriorityTableNumber
ethernetPriorityTableNumber.description: Number of entries in the ethernetPriorityTable.

managementPortAutoNegotiation.name: managementPortAutoNegotiation
managementPortAutoNegotiation.description: This controls whether the configuration of the out-of-band management Ethernet interface is automatically negotiated or forced. WARNING: ONLY USE FORCED AS A LAST RESORT. To operate an Ethernet link at a fixed speed, leave auto negotiation enabled and limit the Auto Neg Advertisement to the desired speed. Only force Ethernet configuration as a last resort if constrained auto negotiation fails. NB: Auto-MDI/MDIX is disabled when Forced is set, and the unit defaults to MDIX, so the correct straight through or crossover cable will be required to establish a connection. NB: both ends of an Ethernet link must be configured identically, as Forced and auto negotiation are NOT compatible. A mixed configuration will cause a duplex mismatch

managementPortAutoNegAdvertisement.name: managementPortAutoNegAdvertisement
managementPortAutoNegAdvertisement.description: This sets the different configurations of the out-of-band management Ethernet interface that will be advertised during auto negotiation. WARNING: Duplex mismatch may result if both ends of the Ethernet link do not have the same settings. Do not use auto negotiation together with a fixed setting at the Ethernet link partner (other end of the link). WARNING: Make sure that you select option(s) that you know your connected equipment can cater for!

managementPortStatus.name: managementPortStatus
managementPortStatus.description: Current status of the out-of-band management Ethernet link

managementPortSpeedAndDuplex.name: managementPortSpeedAndDuplex
managementPortSpeedAndDuplex.description: The current speed and duplex of the out-of-band management Ethernet link

managementPortWirelessDownAlert.name: managementPortWirelessDownAlert
managementPortWirelessDownAlert.description: When enabled, this causes the out-of-band management Ethernet link to be dropped briefly when the wireless link drops. This is so that spanning tree algorithms can quickly detect that there is a problem

managementMode.name: managementMode
managementMode.description: Management mode: Out-of-band management. End-to-end out-of-band mode in which the management agent can be reached from the management port at the local CMU, and (assuming that the wireless link is established) the management port at the remote CMU. Out-of-band local management. (default) Similar to the standard out-of-band mode, except that management frames are not forwarded over the wireless link. In-band management. The management agent can be reached from the data port at the local CMU, and (assuming that the wireless link is established) the data port at the remote CMU. In this mode, the management port is disabled.

managementCommittedInformationRate.name: managementCommittedInformationRate
managementCommittedInformationRate.description: The Management Network Committed Information Rate (CIR). The Management Network guarantees this capacity will be available for management traffic

dataPortPauseFrames.name: dataPortPauseFrames
dataPortPauseFrames.description: Controls whether the bridge tunnels or discards Layer 2 PAUSE frames arriving at the data Ethernet port. Such frames are identified by the destination MAC Address being equal to 01-80-C2-00-00-01

transmitCapacityLimit.name: transmitCapacityLimit
transmitCapacityLimit.description: Transmit capacity is limited by the lower of: 1) the capacity limit specified by the installed License Key. 2) the Ethernet speed negotiated at the other end of the wireless link. Value expressed in 10ths of Mbps. 0 indicates unlimited

transmitCapacityLimitDetail.name: transmitCapacityLimitDetail
transmitCapacityLimitDetail.description: A brief description of the reason (if any) for the limit being applied to the transmit capacity

dataPortEthernetMediaTypeToUse.name: dataPortEthernetMediaTypeToUse
dataPortEthernetMediaTypeToUse.description: The physical media type to use on the data Ethernet port

dataPortCopperForcedConfiguration.name: dataPortCopperForcedConfiguration
dataPortCopperForcedConfiguration.description: This forces the configuration of the copper data Ethernet interface rather than using auto negotiation. THE CONFIGURATION SHOULD ONLY BE FORCED IF YOU ARE HAVING PROBLEMS WITH AUTO NEGOTIATION - AND YOU MUST ENSURE THAT YOU CONFIGURE BOTH THIS UNIT AND THE Ethernet PORT TO WHICH IT IS CONNECTED IDENTICALLY! WARNING: Duplex mismatch may result if both ends of the Ethernet link do not have the same settings. Do not use auto negotiation together with a fixed setting at the Ethernet link partner (other end of the link)

managementPortForcedConfiguration.name: managementPortForcedConfiguration
managementPortForcedConfiguration.description: This forces the configuration of the out-of-band management Ethernet interface rather than using auto negotiation. THE CONFIGURATION SHOULD ONLY BE FORCED IF YOU ARE HAVING PROBLEMS WITH AUTO NEGOTIATION - AND YOU MUST ENSURE THAT YOU CONFIGURE BOTH THIS UNIT AND THE Ethernet PORT TO WHICH IT IS CONNECTED IDENTICALLY! WARNING: Duplex mismatch may result if both ends of the Ethernet link do not have the same settings. Do not use auto negotiation together with a fixed setting at the Ethernet link partner (other end of the link)

l2CPPriorityTableNumber.name: l2CPPriorityTableNumber
l2CPPriorityTableNumber.description: Number of entries in the l2CPPriorityTable.

unknownNetworkPriorityQueueMapping.name: unknownNetworkPriorityQueueMapping
unknownNetworkPriorityQueueMapping.description: Configures the classification of unknown network protocols to an egress queue at the wireless port. Unknown means something other than IP and MPLS

dSCPManagementPriority.name: dSCPManagementPriority
dSCPManagementPriority.description: This Differentiated Services Code Point value will be inserted in the IP Header of all IP Datagrams transmitted by the management interfaces

qOSPriorityScheme.name: qOSPriorityScheme
qOSPriorityScheme.description: Selects classification based on fields in the Ethernet header (Layer 2) or in the Network header (Layer 3). The unit recognises two network layer protocols: IP and MPLS

iPDSCPPriorityTableNumber.name: iPDSCPPriorityTableNumber
iPDSCPPriorityTableNumber.description: Number of entries in the iPDSCPPriorityTable.

mPLSTCPriorityTableNumber.name: mPLSTCPriorityTableNumber
mPLSTCPriorityTableNumber.description: Number of entries in the mPLSTCPriorityTable.

ethernetPriorityQueueMapping.name: ethernetPriorityQueueMapping
ethernetPriorityQueueMapping.description: Configures the classification of this Ethernet priority (also known as IEEE 802.1p value) to an egress queue at the wireless port.

ethernetPriorityTableIndex.name: ethernetPriorityTableIndex
ethernetPriorityTableIndex.description: Ethernet priority flag, used to index values in the ethernetPriorityTable.

l2CPPriorityQueueMapping.name: l2CPPriorityQueueMapping
l2CPPriorityQueueMapping.description: Configures the classification of this layer two control protocol (L2CP) to an egress queue at the wireless port

l2CPPriorityTableIndex.name: l2CPPriorityTableIndex
l2CPPriorityTableIndex.description: layer 2 control protocol, used to index values in the l2CPPriorityTable.

iPDSCPPriorityQueueMapping.name: iPDSCPPriorityQueueMapping
iPDSCPPriorityQueueMapping.description: Configures the classification of this IP differentiated services code point (DSCP) value to an egress queue at the wireless port

iPDSCPPriorityTableIndex.name: iPDSCPPriorityTableIndex
iPDSCPPriorityTableIndex.description: IP DSCP priority flag, used to index values in the iPDSCPPriorityTable

mPLSTCPriorityQueueMapping.name: mPLSTCPriorityQueueMapping
mPLSTCPriorityQueueMapping.description: Configures the classification of this MPLS traffic class (the field formerly known as EXP) to an egress queue at the wireless port

mPLSTCPriorityTableIndex.name: mPLSTCPriorityTableIndex
mPLSTCPriorityTableIndex.description: MPLS TC priority flag, used to index values in the mPLSTCPriorityTable

ethernetFiberSupport.name: ethernetFiberSupport
ethernetFiberSupport.description: Ethernet fiber support availability on this wireless unit

transmitCapacity.name: transmitCapacity
transmitCapacity.description: Maximum capacity the wireless link may provide in the transmit direction. This is restricted by the License Key.

encryptionAlgorithmsAvail.name: encryptionAlgorithmsAvail
encryptionAlgorithmsAvail.description: The Encryption Algorithm(s) available to the wireless link. N.B. The same Encryption Algorithm must be configured at BOTH ends of the link for it to function correctly

linkNameMismatch.name: linkNameMismatch
linkNameMismatch.description: Signaling was received with the wrong Link Name. Either the Link Name is configured differently at each end of the wireless link, or this unit is aligned to the wrong link partner. NB: A change of value during operation may generate an SNMP trap and/or SMTP email alert

alignmentMode.name: alignmentMode
alignmentMode.description: Indicates if the unit is undergoing alignment. NB: a change of state during operation may generate an SNMP trap and/or SMTP email alert

tFTPServerIPAddress.name: tFTPServerIPAddress
tFTPServerIPAddress.description: IP address of the TFTP Server from which the TFTP Software Upgrade File Name will be retrieved

tFTPServerPortNumber.name: tFTPServerPortNumber
tFTPServerPortNumber.description: The port number of the TFTP Server from which the TFTP Software Upgrade File Name will be retrieved

tFTPSoftwareUpgradeFileName.name: tFTPSoftwareUpgradeFileName
tFTPSoftwareUpgradeFileName.description: Filename of the Software Upgrade to be loaded from the TFTP Server

tFTPStartSoftwareUpgrade.name: tFTPStartSoftwareUpgrade
tFTPStartSoftwareUpgrade.description: Write '1' to this attribute to start the TFTP software upgrade process. The attribute will be reset to 0 when the upgrade process has finished

tFTPSoftwareUpgradeStatus.name: tFTPSoftwareUpgradeStatus
tFTPSoftwareUpgradeStatus.description: The current status of the TFTP Software upgrade process

tFTPSoftwareUpgradeStatusText.name: tFTPSoftwareUpgradeStatusText
tFTPSoftwareUpgradeStatusText.description: Descriptive text describing the status of the TFTP Software upgrade process, including any error details

tFTPSoftwareUpgradeStatusAdditionalText.name: tFTPSoftwareUpgradeStatusAdditionalText
tFTPSoftwareUpgradeStatusAdditionalText.description: Any additional text describing the status of the TFTP Software upgrade process, including any error details

hTTPAccessEnabled.name: hTTPAccessEnabled
hTTPAccessEnabled.description: This controls whether or not HTTP access is enabled, i.e. if this is disabled (0) then the unit will not respond to any requests on the HTTP port. Remote management via HTTPS is not affected by this setting. Any change in this setting will not take effect until the unit has been rebooted. (Factory default = Enabled)

telnetAccessEnabled.name: telnetAccessEnabled
telnetAccessEnabled.description: This controls whether or not Telnet access is enabled, i.e. if this is disabled (0) then the unit will not respond to any requests on the TELNET port. Any change in this setting will not take effect until the unit has been rebooted. (Factory default = Disabled)

hTTPPortNumber.name: hTTPPortNumber
hTTPPortNumber.description: This controls the port number for HTTP access. A value of zero will use the default port number. Any change in this setting will not take effect until the unit has been rebooted. (Factory default = 80)

hTTPSPortNumber.name: hTTPSPortNumber
hTTPSPortNumber.description: This controls the port number for HTTPS access. A value of zero will use the default port number. Availability of HTTPS is controlled via the Licence Key. Any change in this setting will not take effect until the unit has been rebooted. (Factory default = 443)

telnetPortNumber.name: telnetPortNumber
telnetPortNumber.description: This controls the port number for TELNET access. A value of zero will use the default port number. Any change in this setting will not take effect until the unit has been rebooted. (Factory default = 23)

hTTPSAccessEnabled.name: hTTPSAccessEnabled
hTTPSAccessEnabled.description: This controls whether or not HTTPS access is enabled, i.e. if this is disabled (0) then the unit will not respond to any requests on the configured HTTPS Port Number. Remote management via HTTP is not affected by this setting. Any change in this setting will not take effect until the unit has been rebooted. (Factory default = Enabled)

remoteMaximumTransmitPower.name: remoteMaximumTransmitPower
remoteMaximumTransmitPower.description: Maximum transmit power the remote wireless unit is permitted to use when establishing and maintaining the wireless link, expressed in tenths of a dBm. Note that when an IRFU is connected rather than an ODU, the transmit power refers to the power at the transceiver output and not the IRFU antenna port. See the User Guide for more details

minModulation.name: minModulation
minModulation.description: When adaptive modulation is enabled, PTP 800 will adapt the modulation mode between a minimum and maximum modulation mode. Depending on the region, minimum and maximum modulation modes will be either derived from the radio license, e.g. FCC and Industry Canada, or will be user adjustable, e.g. ETSI.In general, a modulation mode is defined by two aspects, a modulation and a code rate. This integer attribute identifies the modulation aspect of the minimum modulation mode. For example, if the minimum modulation mode is 16QAM 0.91, this attribute will be set to a value of 2 which identifies a modulation of 16QAM.

minCodeRate.name: minCodeRate
minCodeRate.description: When adaptive modulation is enabled, PTP 800 will adapt the modulation mode between a minimum and maximum modulation mode. Depending on the region, minimum and maximum modulation modes will be either derived from the radio license, e.g. FCC and Industry Canada, or will be user adjustable, e.g. ETSI. In general, a modulation mode is defined by two aspects, a modulation and a code rate. This attribute is equal to 100 times the code rate aspect of the minimum modulation mode. For example, if the minimum modulation mode is 16QAM 0.91, this attribute will be set to a value of 91.

maxModulation.name: maxModulation
maxModulation.description: When adaptive modulation is enabled, PTP 800 will adapt the modulation mode between a minimum and maximum modulation mode. Depending on the region, minimum and maximum modulation modes will be either derived from the radio license, e.g. FCC and Industry Canada, or will be user adjustable, e.g. ETSI. In general, a modulation mode is defined by two aspects, a modulation and a code rate. This integer attribute identifies the modulation aspect of the maximum modulation mode. For example, if the maximum modulation mode is 256QAM 0.91, this attribute will be set to a value of 6 which identifies a modulation of 256QAM.

maxCodeRate.name: maxCodeRate
maxCodeRate.description: When adaptive modulation is enabled, PTP 800 will adapt the modulation mode between a minimum and maximum modulation mode. Depending on the region, minimum and maximum modulation modes will be either derived from the radio license, e.g. FCC and Industry Canada, or will be user adjustable, e.g. ETSI. In general, a modulation mode is defined by two aspects, a modulation and a code rate. This attribute is equal to 100 times the code rate aspect of the maximum modulation mode. For example, if the maximum modulation mode is 256QAM 0.91, this attribute will be set to a value of 91.

receivePower.name: receivePower
receivePower.description: This is the receive power measured by the RFU. When an IRFU transceiver is connected rather than an ODU, the Receive Power refers to the power at the input to the transceiver and not the IRFU antenna port. Expressed in tenths of a dBm.

vectorError.name: vectorError
vectorError.description: Vector Error is a measure of received signal quality. The value is generally in the range from -6 dB to -38 dB, a more negative number indicating a higher quality signal. Expressed in tenths of a dB.

transmitPower.name: transmitPower
transmitPower.description: This is the transmit power of the RFU. When an IRFU transceiver is connected rather than an ODU, the Transmit Power refers to the power at the transceiver output and not the IRFU antenna port. Expressed in tenths of a dBm.

linkLoss.name: linkLoss
linkLoss.description: Link Loss is a measurement of the loss in signal level as the radio wave propagates between the antennas installed at each end of the link. The Link Loss is only accurate if the Antenna Gain and RF Feeder Loss have been configured correctly at both ends of the link. Expressed in tenths of a dB.

receiveCodeRate.name: receiveCodeRate
receiveCodeRate.description: Indicates the code rate applied to the signal being received at the wireless interface. The reported value is the code rate multiplied by 100.

transmitCodeRate.name: transmitCodeRate
transmitCodeRate.description: Indicates the code rate applied to the signal transmitted at the wireless interface. The reported value is the code rate multiplied by 100.

unitOutOfCalibration.name: unitOutOfCalibration
unitOutOfCalibration.description: The unit is out of calibration

encryptionEnabledMismatch.name: encryptionEnabledMismatch
encryptionEnabledMismatch.description: Encryption has been enabled on one end of the wireless link but not the other

wirelessLinkDisabledWarning.name: wirelessLinkDisabledWarning
wirelessLinkDisabledWarning.description: The SNMP ifAdminStatus of the wireless interface has disabled wireless traffic

dataPortDisabledWarning.name: dataPortDisabledWarning
dataPortDisabledWarning.description: The SNMP ifAdminStatus of the data Ethernet interface has disabled Ethernet traffic

dataPortFiberStatus.name: dataPortFiberStatus
dataPortFiberStatus.description: If the fiber interface on the data Ethernet port is not OK, there are three possible causes: 1) the fiber interface has been installed but disabled, 2) the interface could not be established even though no LOS was detected (i.e. an optical carrier was detected, which could be due to a broken TX fiber, or because the interface is disabled at the other end of the fiber link), or 3) the interface could not be established and LOS is detected (i.e. no optical carrier is detected). NB: a change of status may generate an SNMP trap and/or SMTP email alert

dataPortConfigurationMismatch.name: dataPortConfigurationMismatch
dataPortConfigurationMismatch.description: The detection of Ethernet fragments (runt packets) on the data Ethernet port when the link is in full duplex is an indication of an auto-negotiation or forced configuration mismatch

managementPortDisabledWarning.name: managementPortDisabledWarning
managementPortDisabledWarning.description: The SNMP ifAdminStatus of the out-of-band management Ethernet interface has disabled Ethernet traffic

rFUStatus.name: rFUStatus
rFUStatus.description: Current status of the RFU. A state of 'ok' indicates that the RFU is fully operational, although may not be transmitting.

managementPortConfigurationMismatch.name: managementPortConfigurationMismatch
managementPortConfigurationMismatch.description: The detection of Ethernet fragments (runt packets) on the out-of-band management Ethernet port when the link is in full duplex is an indication of an auto-negotiation or forced configuration mismatch

secureModeAlarm.name: secureModeAlarm
secureModeAlarm.description: The secure mode (e.g. FIPS, UC-APL) state of the unit. The secure mode is not configured(1) state indicates that the unit is capable of secure mode operation, and one or more of the following security materials has not been configured: Key Of Keys, Private Key, Public Certificate, DRNG Entropy Status, Wireless Encryption Key. The secure mode mode is configured but not active(2) state indicates that the unit is capable of secure mode operation, and the security material has been configured, but the configuration of interfaces is not consistent with secure mode operation. The secure mode is not supported(3) state indicates that the unit is not capable of secure mode operation. The secure mode capability requires appropriate hardware compatibility, license key and software image.

rFUPlatformCompatibility.name: rFUPlatformCompatibility
rFUPlatformCompatibility.description: This indicates when the RFU currently connected to the CMU does not match the RFU Platform which was installed. Either re-run the Installation Wizard or connect the correct RFU

rFUProtectionCompatibility.name: rFUProtectionCompatibility
rFUProtectionCompatibility.description: This indicates when the IRFU branching unit configuration is not compatible with the protection configuration or if the left hand transceiver has been configured as Secondary or the right hand transceiver has been configured as Primary

sMTPEmailAlert.name: sMTPEmailAlert
sMTPEmailAlert.description: Simple Mail Transfer Protocol is used to send equipment alerts via email to a specified email address. This utility can only be configured by the system administrator

sMTPServerIPAddress.name: sMTPServerIPAddress
sMTPServerIPAddress.description: IP address of the SMTP server

sMTPServerPortNumber.name: sMTPServerPortNumber
sMTPServerPortNumber.description: Port number of the SMTP server

sMTPSourceEmailAddress.name: sMTPSourceEmailAddress
sMTPSourceEmailAddress.description: The 'from' email address used when constructing the automatically generated e-mail message

sMTPDestinationEmailAddress.name: sMTPDestinationEmailAddress
sMTPDestinationEmailAddress.description: The 'to' email address used when constructing the automatically generated e-mail message

sMTPEnabledMessages.name: sMTPEnabledMessages
sMTPEnabledMessages.description: This controls which SMTP messages the unit will send

sNMPPortNumber.name: sNMPPortNumber
sNMPPortNumber.description: The IP port number used to access the SNMP MIB (i.e. Gets and Sets). NB: A system reboot is required to activate changes to this attribute

sNMPCommunityString.name: sNMPCommunityString
sNMPCommunityString.description: The SNMP community string. NB: A system reboot is required to activate changes to this attribute

sNMPTrapVersion.name: sNMPTrapVersion
sNMPTrapVersion.description: The SNMP protocol version to use for SNMP Traps.

sNMPEnabledTraps.name: sNMPEnabledTraps
sNMPEnabledTraps.description: This controls which SNMP Traps the unit will send

enabledDiagnosticAlarms.name: enabledDiagnosticAlarms
enabledDiagnosticAlarms.description: Controls which individual diagnostic alarms are enabled.

enabledDiagnosticProtectionAlarms.name: enabledDiagnosticProtectionAlarms
enabledDiagnosticProtectionAlarms.description: Controls which individual diagnostic protection alarms are enabled.

sNMPTrapTableNumber.name: sNMPTrapTableNumber
sNMPTrapTableNumber.description: Number of entries in the sNMPTrapTable.

sNMPTrapTableIndex.name: sNMPTrapTableIndex
sNMPTrapTableIndex.description: SNMP trap value, used to index the SNMPTrapTable.

sNMPTrapIPAddress.name: sNMPTrapIPAddress
sNMPTrapIPAddress.description: The IP address to which all SNMP Traps are sent. An IP Address of 0.0.0.0 disables all TRAP generation. NB: A system reboot is required to activate changes to this attribute.

sNMPTrapPortNumber.name: sNMPTrapPortNumber
sNMPTrapPortNumber.description: Destination port for SNMP Traps (default=162). A value of 0 will disable the trap receiver. NB: A system reboot is required to activate changes to this attribute.

sNTPSync.name: sNTPSync
sNTPSync.description: If SNTP Sync fails then check the server settings in the Remote Management page, or disable SNTP. NB: a change of state may generate an SNMP trap and/or SMTP email alert

systemClock.name: systemClock
systemClock.description: System clock presented as local time

timeZone.name: timeZone
timeZone.description: Time zone offsets from Greenwich Mean Time (GMT)

sNTPPrimaryServer.name: sNTPPrimaryServer
sNTPPrimaryServer.description: Specifies the primary SNTP server, determining the order in which the servers are tried.

sNTPPrimaryServerDeadTime.name: sNTPPrimaryServerDeadTime
sNTPPrimaryServerDeadTime.description: Time (in seconds) to wait before retrying communications with an unresponsive primary SNTP server. Setting the value to 0 disables the timer.

sNTPServerRetries.name: sNTPServerRetries
sNTPServerRetries.description: Number of times the PTP will retry after an SNTP server fails to respond.

sNTPServerTimeout.name: sNTPServerTimeout
sNTPServerTimeout.description: Time (in seconds) the PTP will wait for a response from an SNTP server.

sNTPServerTableNumber.name: sNTPServerTableNumber
sNTPServerTableNumber.description: Number of entries in the SNTPServerTable.

sNTPServerIPAddress.name: sNTPServerIPAddress
sNTPServerIPAddress.description: The IP address of a valid SNTP server

sNTPServerPortNumber.name: sNTPServerPortNumber
sNTPServerPortNumber.description: The IP port number of the SNTP server. Defaults to port 123.

sNTPServerResponse.name: sNTPServerResponse
sNTPServerResponse.description: The most recent response received from the SNTP server, if used

systemReset.name: systemReset
systemReset.description: Setting this attribute to '1' will cause a system reboot. NB: a system reboot will apply any pending new settings held in memory

secondarySoftwareVersion.name: secondarySoftwareVersion
secondarySoftwareVersion.description: Secondary software version, used when the primary software image is invalid or erased

receiveDataRate.name: receiveDataRate
receiveDataRate.description: Data rate received by the wireless interface. Expressed in kbps, rounded down to nearest 100 kbps.

transmitDataRate.name: transmitDataRate
transmitDataRate.description: Data rate transmitted from the wireless interface. Expressed in kbps, rounded down to nearest 100 kbps.

aggregateDataRate.name: aggregateDataRate
aggregateDataRate.description: Total data rate across the wireless interface summed over both link directions. Expressed in kbps, rounded down to nearest 100 kbps.

wirelessLinkAvailability.name: wirelessLinkAvailability
wirelessLinkAvailability.description: The percentage of time that the unit has been able to successfully demodulate the signal transmitted from the remote end of the link. Calculated since the last reset of the system counters. The reported value is the percentage multiplied by 10000.

wirelessLinkStatus.name: wirelessLinkStatus
wirelessLinkStatus.description: Current status of the wireless link

byteErrorRatio.name: byteErrorRatio
byteErrorRatio.description: The byte error ratio calculated since the last reset of the system counters. The reported value is the ratio multiplied by 10 to the power of 12.

codeWordErrorRatio.name: codeWordErrorRatio
codeWordErrorRatio.description: The wireless link sends data in error correctable blocks called code words. This attribute reports the ratio of uncorrected code words to the total number of code words received since the last reset of the system counters. The reported value is the ratio multiplied by 10 to the power of 12.

encryptionAlgorithm.name: encryptionAlgorithm
encryptionAlgorithm.description: The Encryption Algorithm used by the wireless link. NB: A system reboot is required to activate changes to this attribute. NB: The same Encryption Algorithm must be configured at BOTH ends of the link for it to function correctly

rFUTxBandAboveRx.name: rFUTxBandAboveRx
rFUTxBandAboveRx.description: Yes means RFU transmitter frequency band is above receiver frequency band

rFUTxPowerMin.name: rFUTxPowerMin
rFUTxPowerMin.description: Minimum transmitter power level, in 10ths of dBm

rFUTxPowerMax.name: rFUTxPowerMax
rFUTxPowerMax.description: Maximum transmitter power level, in 10ths of dBm

rFUVersionBank1.name: rFUVersionBank1
rFUVersionBank1.description: RFU firmware version number (nnn/ddMMYY) in bank 1

rFUVersionBank2.name: rFUVersionBank2
rFUVersionBank2.description: RFU firmware version number (nnn/ddMMYY) in bank 2

rFUType.name: rFUType
rFUType.description: RFU type as: RFU platform, frequency band, Tx-Rx frequency spacing, Hi/Lo band and transmit frequency range

rFURxRFSynthLockAlarm.name: rFURxRFSynthLockAlarm
rFURxRFSynthLockAlarm.description: RFU RF receiver out of lock alarm

rFUTxRFSynthLockAlarm.name: rFUTxRFSynthLockAlarm
rFUTxRFSynthLockAlarm.description: RFU RF transmitter out of lock alarm

rFUCommonIFSynthLockAlarm.name: rFUCommonIFSynthLockAlarm
rFUCommonIFSynthLockAlarm.description: Alarm indicating when the common IF RFU synthesizer is out of lock

rFULockoutAlarm.name: rFULockoutAlarm
rFULockoutAlarm.description: RFU locked pending unlock code alarm

rFUCableAlarm.name: rFUCableAlarm
rFUCableAlarm.description: RFU cable detector voltage out of range alarm

rFUCableAttenuationAdjustAlarm.name: rFUCableAttenuationAdjustAlarm
rFUCableAttenuationAdjustAlarm.description: RFU cable attenuator not yet adjusted alarm

rFUTxPowerDegradedAlarm.name: rFUTxPowerDegradedAlarm
rFUTxPowerDegradedAlarm.description: Indicates when the current transmit power is more than 3 dB below or more than 3 dB above the correct transmit power.

rFUTxMuteStatus.name: rFUTxMuteStatus
rFUTxMuteStatus.description: Indicates whether the RFU is transmitting or muted. If it is muted, it will also indicate the reason.

rFUFanAssemblyAlarm.name: rFUFanAssemblyAlarm
rFUFanAssemblyAlarm.description: This indicates when the IRFU transceiver fan assembly has failed. The assembly consists of two fans and if one fan fails, the this will report partial failure. If both fans fail, this will report total failure

rFUHighTemperatureAlarm.name: rFUHighTemperatureAlarm
rFUHighTemperatureAlarm.description: Indicates when the temperature of the IRFU transceiver has risen above either of two thresholds. If the temperature exceeds the High Temperature threshold, the transmit power may reduce. If the temperature exceeds the Very High Temperature threshold, the transceiver will mute the transmitter

rFURFSwitchAlarm.name: rFURFSwitchAlarm
rFURFSwitchAlarm.description: This indicates that an RF switch is not present when it should be or that on the most recent attempt to make this unit active, the IRFU RF Switch was not able to switch to the correct position

rFURxIFSynthLockAlarm.name: rFURxIFSynthLockAlarm
rFURxIFSynthLockAlarm.description: RFU IF receiver out of lock alarm

rFUTxIFSynthLockAlarm.name: rFUTxIFSynthLockAlarm
rFUTxIFSynthLockAlarm.description: RFU IF transmitter out of lock alarm

rFUPowerButtonPressed.name: rFUPowerButtonPressed
rFUPowerButtonPressed.description: IRFU power button have been pressed, IFRU has powered down unexpectedly

rFUConnectedPlatform.name: rFUConnectedPlatform
rFUConnectedPlatform.description: The type of RFU platform currently connected to the CMU

rFUCommonRFSynthLockAlarm.name: rFUCommonRFSynthLockAlarm
rFUCommonRFSynthLockAlarm.description: Alarm indicating when the common RFU RF synthesizer is out of lock

rFUBranchingConfiguration.name: rFUBranchingConfiguration
rFUBranchingConfiguration.description: When an IRFU is being installed, the configuration of the IRFU branching unit must be configured. Please see the User Guide for further details

rFUTransceiverLocation.name: rFUTransceiverLocation
rFUTransceiverLocation.description: When a 2+0 IRFU is being installed, the user must configure which of the two IRFU transceivers the CMU is controlling in order to ensure correct operation

rFURfSwitchCableAlarm.name: rFURfSwitchCableAlarm
rFURfSwitchCableAlarm.description: The RF switch in the IRFU is indicating an invalid switch position. The most likely cause is a fault or a disconnection of the cable which connects the transceiver to the RF switch

rFUReceiveBranchingUnitLoss.name: rFUReceiveBranchingUnitLoss
rFUReceiveBranchingUnitLoss.description: The receive loss in the IRFU branching unit, expressed in tenths of a dB. The branching unit is a component of the IRFU which is situated between the IRFU transceiver and IRFU antenna port. It provides the necessary filtering, isolation and coupling.

rFUTransmitBranchingUnitLoss.name: rFUTransmitBranchingUnitLoss
rFUTransmitBranchingUnitLoss.description: The transmit loss in the IRFU branching unit, expressed in tenths of a dB. The branching unit is a component of the IRFU which is situated between the IRFU transceiver and IRFU antenna port. It provides the necessary filtering, isolation and coupling.

radioLicenseTxFreq.name: radioLicenseTxFreq
radioLicenseTxFreq.description: Radio license transmit frequency in kHz

radioLicenseRxFreq.name: radioLicenseRxFreq
radioLicenseRxFreq.description: Radio license receive frequency in kHz

radioLicenseMaxEIRP.name: radioLicenseMaxEIRP
radioLicenseMaxEIRP.description: Maximum Effective Isotropic Radiated Power (EIRP) permitted by the license. Expressed in 10ths of dBm

radioLicenseCodeRate.name: radioLicenseCodeRate
radioLicenseCodeRate.description: Radio license code rate, multiplied by 100 to give two decimal places of precision

radioLicenseIncompatibleAlarm.name: radioLicenseIncompatibleAlarm
radioLicenseIncompatibleAlarm.description: Indicates if the radio license is incompatible with the attached RFU. Re-run Installation to correct the issue

radioLicenseMinModulation.name: radioLicenseMinModulation
radioLicenseMinModulation.description: Certain licensing authorities, for example FCC and Industry Canada, require adaptive modulation to be bound by a minimum and maximum modulation mode as defined by the radio license. This attribute is only of significance in such regions and when adaptive modulation is enabled. For other regions, for example ETSI, minimum and maximum modulation mode are directly adjustable by the user and are not defined by the radio license. In general, a modulation mode is defined by two aspects, a modulation and a code rate. This integer attribute identifies the modulation aspect of the RadioLicenseMinModMode attribute required by the radio license. For example, if RadioLicenseMinModMode is configured for 16QAM 0.79, this attribute will be set to a value of 2 which identifies a modulation of 16QAM.

radioLicenseMinCodeRate.name: radioLicenseMinCodeRate
radioLicenseMinCodeRate.description: Certain licensing authorities, for example FCC and Industry Canada, require adaptive modulation to be bound by a minimum and maximum modulation mode as defined by the radio license. This attribute is only of significance in such regions and when adaptive modulation is enabled. For other regions, for example ETSI, minimum and maximum modulation mode are directly adjustable by the user and are not defined by the radio license. In general, a modulation mode is defined by two aspects, a modulation and a code rate. This attribute is equal to 100 times the code rate aspect of the RadioLicenseMinModMode attribute required by the radio license. For example, if RadioLicenseMinModMode is configured for QPSK 0.80, this attribute will read 80.

radioLicenseMaxModulation.name: radioLicenseMaxModulation
radioLicenseMaxModulation.description: Certain licensing authorities, for example FCC and Industry Canada, require adaptive modulation to be bound by a minimum and maximum modulation mode as defined by the radio license. This attribute is only of significance in such regions and when adaptive modulation is enabled. For other regions, for example ETSI, minimum and maximum modulation mode are directly adjustable by the user and are not defined by the radio license. In general, a modulation mode is defined by two aspects, a modulation and a code rate. This integer attribute identifies the modulation aspect of the RadioLicenseMaxModMode attribute required by the radio license. For example, if RadioLicenseMaxModMode is configured for 256QAM 0.91, this attribute will be set to a value of 6 which identifies a modulation of 256QAM.

radioLicenseMaxCodeRate.name: radioLicenseMaxCodeRate
radioLicenseMaxCodeRate.description: Certain licensing authorities, for example FCC and Industry Canada, require adaptive modulation to be bound by a minimum and maximum modulation mode as defined by the radio license. This attribute is only of significance in such regions and when adaptive modulation is enabled. For other regions, for example ETSI, minimum and maximum modulation mode are directly adjustable by the user and are not defined by the radio license. In general, a modulation mode is defined by two aspects, a modulation and a code rate. This attribute is equal to 100 times the code rate aspect of the RadioLicenseMaxModMode attribute required by the radio license. For example, if RadioLicenseMaxModMode is configured for 256QAM 0.91, this attribute will read 91.

protection.name: protection
protection.description: PTP 800 supports a 1+1 Hot Standby configuration where the wireless link is protected against hardware failure. This requires the installation of redundant equipment at each end of the wireless link including a secondary CMU and RFU. At a given end of the wireless link, only one CMU / RFU is Active at any one time, the neighbor CMU / RFU being Inactive. When a fault is detected on the Active CMU / RFU, the Active role will automatically switch to the Inactive CMU / RFU. To enable functionality associated with this feature, this attribute must be configured for a setting of 1+1.

faultProtectionSwitching.name: faultProtectionSwitching
faultProtectionSwitching.description: In a 1+1 Hot Standby configuration, protection switching on detection of a fault can be enabled/disabled using this attribute.

primarySecondaryMode.name: primarySecondaryMode
primarySecondaryMode.description: At a given end of a 1+1 Hot Standby configuration, one CMU must be configured as Primary, the other CMU as Secondary. When a Protected Link initialises with no faults, the CMUs configured as Primary will become the Active CMUs, that is, the Primary CMUs are the preferred CMUs. When RFUs are connected to the antenna via an Asymmetric Coupler, the RFU which is connected to the Primary CMU should be connected to the Main path of the coupler. This is the path with the lowest loss.

numberOfAntennas.name: numberOfAntennas
numberOfAntennas.description: This must be configured to match the number of antennas installed at this end of the link.

primaryRecovery.name: primaryRecovery
primaryRecovery.description: At a given end of a 1+1 Hot Standby configuration, the CMU configured as Primary is the preferred unit to take the Active role. If the Primary Recovery attribute is set to Enabled at a given end, a protection switch back to the preferred Primary CMU / RFU will occur autonomously if it has stayed free of faults for a configurable period of time determined by the Primary Recovery Period.

primaryRecoveryPeriod.name: primaryRecoveryPeriod
primaryRecoveryPeriod.description: At a given end of a 1+1 Hot Standby configuration, the CMU configured as Primary is the preferred unit to take the Active role. If the Primary Recovery attribute is set to Enabled at a given end, a protection switch back to the preferred Primary CMU / RFU will occur autonomously if it has stayed free of faults for a configurable period of time determined by the Primary Recovery Period.

requestedProtectionState.name: requestedProtectionState
requestedProtectionState.description: In a 1+1 Hot Standby configuration, only one CMU / RFU at a given end of the link is Active at any one time, the neighbor CMU / RFU being Inactive. Use the Requested Protection State attribute to request whether this CMU / RFU should be in the Active or Inactive state.

antennaReceiveLevelDeltaThreshold.name: antennaReceiveLevelDeltaThreshold
antennaReceiveLevelDeltaThreshold.description: At a given end of a 1+1 Hot Standby configuration, a CMU will raise an alarm to the management system when the measured receive level adjusted by antenna gain and feeder loss is less than that of its neighbor by more than the Antenna Receive Level Delta Threshold.

antennaReceiveLevelMeasurementWindow.name: antennaReceiveLevelMeasurementWindow
antennaReceiveLevelMeasurementWindow.description: At a given end of a 1+1 Hot Standby configuration, a CMU will raise an alarm to the management system when the measured receive level adjusted by antenna gain and feeder loss is less than that of its neighbor by more than the Antenna Receive Level Delta Threshold. The measurements are averaged over the most recent Antenna Receive Level Measurement Window.

fiberY.name: fiberY
fiberY.description: One or both ends of a 1+1 Hot Standby system can be connected to the network using an 'Optical-Y Splitter Kit per end'. This end configuration provides a single fiber interface to the network. Any end which is connected to the network using this method must have the Fiber Y attribute set to Enabled. Please note: CMUs must be loaded with boot code version 03-00 or later and recovery version 04-00 or later for Fiber Y to work correctly.

rxDiversityVlanTpid.name: rxDiversityVlanTpid
rxDiversityVlanTpid.description: When Receive Diversity is enabled, the Inactive CMU sends Rx Diversity Ethernet Frames to the Active CMU. These Ethernet Frames must be VLAN tagged and this attribute controls whether the frames are tagged using the TPID defined by 802.1Q or the TPID defined by 802.1ad.

rxDiversityVid.name: rxDiversityVid
rxDiversityVid.description: When Receive Diversity is enabled, the Inactive CMU sends Rx Diversity Ethernet Frames to the Active CMU. These Ethernet Frames must be VLAN tagged and this attribute controls the VLAN Identifier

protectionAvailabilityStatus.name: protectionAvailabilityStatus
protectionAvailabilityStatus.description: In a 1+1 Hot Standby configuration, the Protection Availability Status attribute indicates whether the Active unit is currently being protected by the Inactive unit. If it isn't being protected, the Active unit will report Not Protected and the Inactive unit will report Not Protecting.

protectionConfigurationStatus.name: protectionConfigurationStatus
protectionConfigurationStatus.description: In a 1+1 Hot Standby configuration, this attribute will indicate whether the configuration will support protection.

protectionState.name: protectionState
protectionState.description: In a 1+1 Hot Standby configuration, only one CMU / RFU at a given end of the link is Active at any one time, the neighbor CMU / RFU being Inactive. The Protection State attribute indicates whether a CMU / RFU is in the Active or Inactive state.

activeUnit.name: activeUnit
activeUnit.description: At a given end of a 1+1 Hot Standby configuration, one CMU must be configured as Primary, the other CMU as Secondary. When a Protected Link initialises with no faults, the CMU configured as Primary will become the Active CMU, that is, the Primary CMU is the preferred CMUs. The Active Unit attribute indicates whether the active unit is configured as Primary or Secondary.

protectionSwitchCause.name: protectionSwitchCause
protectionSwitchCause.description: In a 1+1 Hot Standby configuration, the Protection Switch Cause attribute reports the reason for the last protection switch.

endId.name: endId
endId.description: In a 1+1 Hot Standby configuration, the End Id contains the IP address of neighboring CMUs starting with the highest IP address and with a space separating the addresses. It is a single identifier of neighboring CMUs.

neighborIPAddress.name: neighborIPAddress
neighborIPAddress.description: In a 1+1 Hot Standby configuration, the Neighbor IP Address identifies the IP Address of the neighbor CMU connected via the Protection Interface.

neighborMACAddress.name: neighborMACAddress
neighborMACAddress.description: In a 1+1 Hot Standby configuration, the Neighbor MAC Address identifies the MAC Address of the neighbor CMU connected via the Protection Interface.

wirelessReceiveSignalStatus.name: wirelessReceiveSignalStatus
wirelessReceiveSignalStatus.description: The Wireless Receive Signal Status indicates if the receiver is able to demodulate the transmit signal from the remote end of the link. If it cannot demodulate the signal, a protection switch may occur in a system configured for 1+1 Hot Standby.

licensedTransmitCapacityStatus.name: licensedTransmitCapacityStatus
licensedTransmitCapacityStatus.description: In a 1+1 Hot Standby configuration, the Licensed Transmit Capacity Status attribute indicates when the Licensed Transmit Capacity is below that of its neighbor.

dataPortEthernetSpeedStatus.name: dataPortEthernetSpeedStatus
dataPortEthernetSpeedStatus.description: In a 1+1 Hot Standby configuration, the Data Port Ethernet Speed Status attribute indicates if the Ethernet Speed of the Data Port is below that of its neighbor.

managementPortEthernetSpeedStatus.name: managementPortEthernetSpeedStatus
managementPortEthernetSpeedStatus.description: In a 1+1 Hot Standby configuration, the Management Port Ethernet Speed Status attribute indicates if the Ethernet Speed of the Management Port is below that of its neighbor.

protectionInterfaceStatus.name: protectionInterfaceStatus
protectionInterfaceStatus.description: In a 1+1 Hot Standby configuration, information is shared between neighbor CMUs over the Protection Interface. The Protection Interface Status attribute reports whether the neighbor CMU is successfully responding, physically disconnected or whether it is physically connected but not responding, e.g. powered down.

remotePrimaryIPAddress.name: remotePrimaryIPAddress
remotePrimaryIPAddress.description: In a 1+1 Hot Standby configuration, the Remote Primary IP Address reports the IP address of the CMU which is configured as Primary at the remote end of the wireless link.

remoteSecondaryIPAddress.name: remoteSecondaryIPAddress
remoteSecondaryIPAddress.description: In a 1+1 Hot Standby configuration, the Remote Secondary IP Address reports the IP address of the CMU which is configured as Secondary at the remote end of the wireless link.

remotePrimaryMACAddress.name: remotePrimaryMACAddress
remotePrimaryMACAddress.description: In a 1+1 Hot Standby configuration, the Remote Primary MAC Address reports the MAC address of the CMU which is configured as Primary at the remote end of the wireless link.

remoteSecondaryMACAddress.name: remoteSecondaryMACAddress
remoteSecondaryMACAddress.description: In a 1+1 Hot Standby configuration, the Remote Secondary MAC Address reports the MAC address of the CMU which is configured as Secondary at the remote end of the wireless link.

remotePrimarySecondaryMode.name: remotePrimarySecondaryMode
remotePrimarySecondaryMode.description: In a 1+1 Hot Standby configuration, this attribute identifies whether the Active Unit at the remote end of the link is configured as Primary or Secondary.

transmitterStatus.name: transmitterStatus
transmitterStatus.description: Indicates whether the RFU is transmitting or muted. In a 1+1 Hot Standby configuration, it will also indicate if the RFU is Inactive and therefore ready to transmit.

endWirelessReceiveSignalStatus.name: endWirelessReceiveSignalStatus
endWirelessReceiveSignalStatus.description: The End Wireless Receive Signal Status indicates if the end of a link is unable to demodulate the signal transmitted from the remote end of the link. When Protection is set to 1+1 Hot Standby, this attribute will indicate Not Detected if the Active CMU is unable to demodulate the wireless signal. When Receive Diversity is enabled, this attribute will indicate Not Detected if both the Active and Inactive CMUs are unable to demodulate the wireless signal.

rxDiversityDataPortStatus.name: rxDiversityDataPortStatus
rxDiversityDataPortStatus.description: When Receive Diversity is enabled, the Inactive CMU sends Rx Diversity Ethernet Frames to the Active CMU. Before sending these frames, the Data Port MUST be negotiated at 1000 Mbps. This attribute indicates if this is not the case

rxDiversityAvailabilityStatus.name: rxDiversityAvailabilityStatus
rxDiversityAvailabilityStatus.description: The Rx Diversity Availability Status attribute will indicate when Receive Diversity is not operating correctly, either due to a fault or due to an incorrect configuration

rxDiversityConfigurationStatus.name: rxDiversityConfigurationStatus
rxDiversityConfigurationStatus.description: For Receive Diversity to operate correctly, certain attributes must be configured correctly on both neighbor CMUs. The Rx Diversity Configuration Status attribute will indicate when this is not the case

rxDiversityNeighborCompatibility.name: rxDiversityNeighborCompatibility
rxDiversityNeighborCompatibility.description: For Receive Diversity to operate correctly, both neighbor CMUs must both be configured with the Protection attribute set to 1+1 Hot Standby with Rx Diversity. The Rx Diversity Neighbor Compatibility attribute indicates when the neighbor CMU is configured to a different setting

rxDiversityVlanTpidNeighborCompatibility.name: rxDiversityVlanTpidNeighborCompatibility
rxDiversityVlanTpidNeighborCompatibility.description: For Receive Diversity to operate correctly, both neighbor CMUs must be configured with the same value of Rx Diversity VLAN TPID. The Rx Diversity VLAN TPID Neighbor Compatibility attribute indicates when this is not the case

rxDiversityVidNeighborCompatibility.name: rxDiversityVidNeighborCompatibility
rxDiversityVidNeighborCompatibility.description: For Receive Diversity to operate correctly, both neighbor CMUs must be configured with the same value of Rx Diversity VID. The Rx Diversity VID Neighbor Compatibility attribute indicates when this is not the case

activeCodeWordCount.name: activeCodeWordCount
activeCodeWordCount.description: The Active Code Word Count reports the number of code words received over the wireless interface whilst the CMU / RFU is in the Active role of a 1+1 Hot Standby configuration. The count is since the last statistics reset.

activeCodeWordErrorCount.name: activeCodeWordErrorCount
activeCodeWordErrorCount.description: The Active Code Word Error Count reports the number of code word errors which have been detected at the wireless interface whilst the CMU / RFU is in the Active role of a 1+1 Hot Standby configuration. The count is since the last statistics reset.

activeByteCount.name: activeByteCount
activeByteCount.description: The Active Byte Count reports the number of bytes received over the wireless interface whilst the CMU / RFU is in the Active role of a 1+1 Hot Standby configuration. The count is since the last statistics reset.

activeByteErrorCount.name: activeByteErrorCount
activeByteErrorCount.description: The Active Byte Error Count reports the number of byte errors which have been detected at the wireless interface whilst the CMU / RFU is in the Active role of a 1+1 Hot Standby configuration. The count is since the last statistics reset.

activeAvailableTime.name: activeAvailableTime
activeAvailableTime.description: The Active Available Time reports the time which the Wireless Link Status has been Up whilst the CMU/RFU has been in the Active role of a 1+1 Hot Standby configuration. The reported time is since the last statistics reset.

activeCounterMeasurementPeriod.name: activeCounterMeasurementPeriod
activeCounterMeasurementPeriod.description: For a 1+1 Hot Standby link, the elapsed time that the Protection State of the unit has been in the active state since the last reset of the system counters.

activeWirelessLinkAvailability.name: activeWirelessLinkAvailability
activeWirelessLinkAvailability.description: For a 1+1 Hot Standby link, the percentage of time that the unit has been able to successfully demodulate the signal transmitted from the remote end of the link whilst the Protecion State of the unit has been active. This attribute is not updated whilst the Protection State is inactive. Calculated since the last reset of the system counters. The reported value is the percentage multiplied by 10000

activeCodeWordErrorRatio.name: activeCodeWordErrorRatio
activeCodeWordErrorRatio.description: The wireless link sends data in error correctable blocks called code words. For a 1+1 Hot Standby link, this attribute reports the ratio of uncorrected code words to the total number of code words received whilst the Protecion State of the unit has been active. This ratio is not updated whilst the Protection State is inactive. Calculated since the last reset of the system counters. The reported value is the ratio multiplied by 10 to the power of 12

activeByteErrorRatio.name: activeByteErrorRatio
activeByteErrorRatio.description: For a 1+1 Hot Standby link, the Byte Error Ratio measured by the unit whilst the Protecion State has been active. This ratio is not updated whilst the Protection State is inactive. Calculated since the last reset of the system counters. The reported value is the ratio multiplied by 10 to the power of 12

syslogClient.name: syslogClient
syslogClient.description: Enable or disable the syslog client

syslogState.name: syslogState
syslogState.description: The syslog service has been enabled or disabled

longitude.name: longitude
longitude.description: The longitude of the unit, measured in decimal degrees. This object is set by the SNMP manager and has no internal function.

latitude.name: latitude
latitude.description: The latitude of the unit, measured in decimal degrees. This object is set by the SNMP manager and has no internal function.

altitude.name: altitude
altitude.description: The altitude of the unit, measured in metres. This object is set by the SNMP manager and has no internal function.

dataPortStatusTrap.name: dataPortStatusTrap
dataPortStatusTrap.description: Current status of the data Ethernet link. NB: a change of state may generate an SNMP trap and/or SMTP email alert

linkNameMismatchTrap.name: linkNameMismatchTrap
linkNameMismatchTrap.description: Signaling was received with the wrong Link Name. Either the Link Name is configured differently at each end of the wireless link, or this unit is aligned to the wrong link partner. NB: A change of value during operation may generate an SNMP trap and/or SMTP email alert

alignmentModeTrap.name: alignmentModeTrap
alignmentModeTrap.description: Indicates if the unit is undergoing alignment. NB: a change of state during operation may generate an SNMP trap and/or SMTP email alert

unitOutOfCalibrationTrap.name: unitOutOfCalibrationTrap
unitOutOfCalibrationTrap.description: The unit is out of calibration

encryptionEnabledMismatchTrap.name: encryptionEnabledMismatchTrap
encryptionEnabledMismatchTrap.description: Encryption has been enabled on one end of the wireless link but not the other

wirelessLinkDisabledWarningTrap.name: wirelessLinkDisabledWarningTrap
wirelessLinkDisabledWarningTrap.description: The SNMP ifAdminStatus of the wireless interface has disabled wireless traffic

dataPortDisabledWarningTrap.name: dataPortDisabledWarningTrap
dataPortDisabledWarningTrap.description: The SNMP ifAdminStatus of the data Ethernet interface has disabled Ethernet traffic

dataPortFiberStatusTrap.name: dataPortFiberStatusTrap
dataPortFiberStatusTrap.description: If the fiber interface on the data Ethernet port is not OK, there are three possible causes: 1) the fiber interface has been installed but disabled, 2) the interface could not be established even though no LOS was detected (i.e. an optical carrier was detected, which could be due to a broken TX fiber, or because the interface is disabled at the other end of the fiber link), or 3) the interface could not be established and LOS is detected (i.e. no optical carrier is detected). NB: a change of status may generate an SNMP trap and/or SMTP email alert

dataPortConfigurationMismatchTrap.name: dataPortConfigurationMismatchTrap
dataPortConfigurationMismatchTrap.description: The detection of Ethernet fragments (runt packets) on the data Ethernet port when the link is in full duplex is an indication of an auto-negotiation or forced configuration mismatch

sNTPSyncTrap.name: sNTPSyncTrap
sNTPSyncTrap.description: If SNTP Sync fails then check the server settings in the Remote Management page, or disable SNTP. NB: a change of state may generate an SNMP trap and/or SMTP email alert

managementPortStatusTrap.name: managementPortStatusTrap
managementPortStatusTrap.description: Current status of the out-of-band management Ethernet link

managementPortDisabledWarningTrap.name: managementPortDisabledWarningTrap
managementPortDisabledWarningTrap.description: The SNMP ifAdminStatus of the out-of-band management Ethernet interface has disabled Ethernet traffic

rFUStatusTrap.name: rFUStatusTrap
rFUStatusTrap.description: Current status of the RFU. A state of 'ok' indicates that the RFU is fully operational, although may not be transmitting.

managementPortConfigurationMismatchTrap.name: managementPortConfigurationMismatchTrap
managementPortConfigurationMismatchTrap.description: The detection of Ethernet fragments (runt packets) on the out-of-band management Ethernet port when the link is in full duplex is an indication of an auto-negotiation or forced configuration mismatch

wirelessLinkStatusTrap.name: wirelessLinkStatusTrap
wirelessLinkStatusTrap.description: Current status of the wireless link

protectionAvailabilityStatusTrap.name: protectionAvailabilityStatusTrap
protectionAvailabilityStatusTrap.description: In a 1+1 Hot Standby configuration, the Protection Availability Status attribute indicates whether the Active unit is currently being protected by the Inactive unit. If it isn't being protected, the Active unit will report Not Protected and the Inactive unit will report Not Protecting.

protectionConfigurationStatusTrap.name: protectionConfigurationStatusTrap
protectionConfigurationStatusTrap.description: In a 1+1 Hot Standby configuration, this attribute will indicate whether the configuration will support protection.

protectionStateTrap.name: protectionStateTrap
protectionStateTrap.description: In a 1+1 Hot Standby configuration, only one CMU / RFU at a given end of the link is Active at any one time, the neighbor CMU / RFU being Inactive. The Protection State attribute indicates whether a CMU / RFU is in the Active or Inactive state.

wirelessReceiveSignalStatusTrap.name: wirelessReceiveSignalStatusTrap
wirelessReceiveSignalStatusTrap.description: The Wireless Receive Signal Status indicates if the receiver is able to demodulate the transmit signal from the remote end of the link. If it cannot demodulate the signal, a protection switch may occur in a system configured for 1+1 Hot Standby.

licensedTransmitCapacityStatusTrap.name: licensedTransmitCapacityStatusTrap
licensedTransmitCapacityStatusTrap.description: In a 1+1 Hot Standby configuration, the Licensed Transmit Capacity Status attribute indicates when the Licensed Transmit Capacity is below that of its neighbor.

dataPortEthernetSpeedStatusTrap.name: dataPortEthernetSpeedStatusTrap
dataPortEthernetSpeedStatusTrap.description: In a 1+1 Hot Standby configuration, the Data Port Ethernet Speed Status attribute indicates if the Ethernet Speed of the Data Port is below that of its neighbor.

managementPortEthernetSpeedStatusTrap.name: managementPortEthernetSpeedStatusTrap
managementPortEthernetSpeedStatusTrap.description: In a 1+1 Hot Standby configuration, the Management Port Ethernet Speed Status attribute indicates if the Ethernet Speed of the Management Port is below that of its neighbor.

protectionInterfaceStatusTrap.name: protectionInterfaceStatusTrap
protectionInterfaceStatusTrap.description: In a 1+1 Hot Standby configuration, information is shared between neighbor CMUs over the Protection Interface. The Protection Interface Status attribute reports whether the neighbor CMU is successfully responding, physically disconnected or whether it is physically connected but not responding, e.g. powered down.

syslogStateTrap.name: syslogStateTrap
syslogStateTrap.description: The syslog service has been enabled or disabled

syslogLocalNearlyFullTrap.name: syslogLocalNearlyFullTrap
syslogLocalNearlyFullTrap.description: The syslog local log is nearly full (90%)

syslogLocalWrappedTrap.name: syslogLocalWrappedTrap
syslogLocalWrappedTrap.description: The syslog local log has wrapped

secureModeAlarmTrap.name: secureModeAlarmTrap
secureModeAlarmTrap.description: The secure mode (e.g. FIPS, UC-APL) state of the unit. The secure mode is not configured(1) state indicates that the unit is capable of secure mode operation, and one or more of the following security materials has not been configured: Key Of Keys, Private Key, Public Certificate, DRNG Entropy Status, Wireless Encryption Key. The secure mode mode is configured but not active(2) state indicates that the unit is capable of secure mode operation, and the security material has been configured, but the configuration of interfaces is not consistent with secure mode operation. The secure mode is not supported(3) state indicates that the unit is not capable of secure mode operation. The secure mode capability requires appropriate hardware compatibility, license key and software image.

endWirelessReceiveSignalStatusTrap.name: endWirelessReceiveSignalStatusTrap
endWirelessReceiveSignalStatusTrap.description: The End Wireless Receive Signal Status indicates if the end of a link is unable to demodulate the signal transmitted from the remote end of the link. When Protection is set to 1+1 Hot Standby, this attribute will indicate Not Detected if the Active CMU is unable to demodulate the wireless signal. When Receive Diversity is enabled, this attribute will indicate Not Detected if both the Active and Inactive CMUs are unable to demodulate the wireless signal.

rxDiversityDataPortStatusTrap.name: rxDiversityDataPortStatusTrap
rxDiversityDataPortStatusTrap.description: When Receive Diversity is enabled, the Inactive CMU sends Rx Diversity Ethernet Frames to the Active CMU. Before sending these frames, the Data Port MUST be negotiated at 1000 Mbps. This attribute indicates if this is not the case

rxDiversityAvailabilityStatusTrap.name: rxDiversityAvailabilityStatusTrap
rxDiversityAvailabilityStatusTrap.description: The Rx Diversity Availability Status attribute will indicate when Receive Diversity is not operating correctly, either due to a fault or due to an incorrect configuration

rxDiversityConfigurationStatusTrap.name: rxDiversityConfigurationStatusTrap
rxDiversityConfigurationStatusTrap.description: For Receive Diversity to operate correctly, certain attributes must be configured correctly on both neighbor CMUs. The Rx Diversity Configuration Status attribute will indicate when this is not the case

rFUPowerButtonPressedTrap.name: rFUPowerButtonPressedTrap
rFUPowerButtonPressedTrap.description: IRFU power button have been pressed, IFRU has powered down unexpectedly

syslogClientTrap.name: syslogClientTrap
syslogClientTrap.description: Enable or disable the syslog client
